@guozhangwang The problem of firing callback in the caller thread is that this can cause out of order callback invoking. For example, we called producer.send() on 10 messages to a partition and after that buffer is full. Now if user send the 11th message they will receive TimeoutException which is an API exception. callback of the 11th message will be fired in the user thread before the callbacks of the previous 11 messages are invoked in the sender thread.

Also, if an application wants order guarantee without data loss. They will close the producer with zero timeout in the callback. However, this assumption is based on the fact that the callback is only fired in the sender thread. If an exception is thrown in the user thread, it is always safe for user to retry.

Another thing a little weird is that It seems currently timeoutException is an API exception because it extends from RetriableException. But TimeoutException seems a purely client side exception.  Maybe we should just extend from runtime exception. But this is orthogonal to this fix.

@becketqin I agree with you about the out-or-order callback triggering issue. As for the fix, I think we can either 1) change all the ApiExceptions to KafkaExceptions to still guarantee that they are only thrown in callback, hence compatible APIs; 2) push the exception to the corresponding batch to let the sender thread to trigger these exceptions in order instead of throwing it directly from caller thread.

AFAIK there are two exceptions that can be thrown by caller thread: RecordTooLargeException and TimeoutException (I may miss any exceptions). I think TimeoutException is treated as RetriableException since in consumer client, it is used to decide that metadata refresh can be retried upon timed up; and RecordTooLargeException is treated as an ApiException since it could be returned from broker and has a corresponding error code. So I feel both of them cannot be simply moved out of ApiException category.

So I'm thinking the most appropriate fix would be 2) above, it would be more complex than your proposal, but it guarantees the separate handling as @ijuma mentioned.
